TB6612FNG:
Takes low-power signals from a controller.
Drives high-power motors safely.
can control:
2 DC motors OR,
1 stepper motor
Why do we need it?:
A board like the Arduino Nano:
Cannot supply enough current to run motors.
Can get damaged if connected directly.
So TB6612FNG acts as a middle layer (driver).

How it works (Simple):
Step-by-step process:
1. Arduino sends signals
Direction signals → AIN1, AIN2
Speed signal → PWM (PWMA)
2. TB6612FNG processes signals
Uses internal H-Bridge circuit
3. Motor runs
Gets power from battery (VM pin)
Rotates forward/backward

Power:
VM → Motor power (battery)
VCC → Logic power (Arduino 5V)
GND → Ground
Control:
AIN1, AIN2 → Direction (Motor A)
BIN1, BIN2 → Direction (Motor B)
PWMA, PWMB → Speed (PWM)
STBY → Enable (must be HIGH)

Power Flow:
Battery → VM → Motor
Arduino → Control signals → TB6612FNG
Advantages:
Efficient (less heat)
Small size
Better than L298N
Good for battery robots

TB6612FNG PIN CONFIGURATION:

This motor driver can control 2 motors (Motor A & Motor B).
1. Power Pins
VM → Motor power supply (battery 5V–12V)
VCC → Logic power (from Arduino, usually 5V)
GND → Ground (must be common with Arduino)
2. Motor Output Pins
Motor A:
A01, A02 → Connect to Motor A
Motor B:
B01, B02 → Connect to Motor B
3. Control Pins
Motor A Control
AIN1, AIN2 → Direction control
PWMA → Speed control (PWM)
Motor B Control
BIN1, BIN2 → Direction control
PWMB → Speed control (PWM)
4. Standby Pin
STBY (Standby)
LOW → Driver OFF
HIGH → Driver ON
How Pins Work Together
To move Motor A forward:
AIN1 = HIGH
AIN2 = LOW
PWMA = PWM signal
To reverse:
AIN1 = LOW
AIN2 = HIGH

Power → VM, VCC, GND  
Control → AIN1, AIN2, BIN1, BIN2  
Speed → PWMA, PWMB  
Motor → A01, A02, B01, B02  
Enable → STBY  
Must be HIGH for motors to work

Always connect common GND
Don’t forget STBY = HIGH
Use PWM pins for speed control
Use separate battery for motors (VM)

